headline: Airline Results Suggest Less Wealthy Americans Are Already Feeling Tariffs
summary: On Thursday, American Airlines pulled its full-year guidance, echoing moves by carriers such as Southwest Airlines, Delta Air Lines and Alaska Air.  United Airlines has been more creative by issuing an outlook for a stable economy, and another for a tariff-induced recession.  American’s results contained another key piece of information: There is “significant weakness” in demand coming from travelers who book through indirect channels such as online portals.

raw.headline: Airline Results Suggest Less Wealthy Americans Are Already Feeling Tariffs
raw.summary: On Thursday, American Airlines pulled its full-year guidance, echoing moves by carriers such as Southwest Airlines, Delta Air Lines and Alaska Air.  United Airlines has been more creative by issuing an outlook for a stable economy, and another for a tariff-induced recession.  American’s results contained another key piece of information: There is “significant weakness” in demand coming from travelers who book through indirect channels such as online portals.

headline: Trade war and leery travelers have airlines trimming flights and withdrawing financial guidance
summary: Major U.S. airlines are reducing their flight schedules and revising or withdrawing their profit outlooks for the year due to less domestic travel demand as sentiment about the national and global economies sours.  American Airlines pulled its financial guidance for 2025 on Thursday, joining rivals Southwest and Delta in declaring the economic outlook too uncertain to provide full-year forecasts.  “We came off a strong fourth quarter, saw decent business in January, and really domestic leisure travel fell off considerably as we went into the February time frame,” American Airlines CEO Robert Isom told CNBC.
